article.description:
Katie Smith scored 14 of her 18 points in the second half in
the Lynx's 76-68 victory over Phoenix on Saturday night.
article.headline: Phoenix shot just 33 percent in second half
article.linkText: Mercury squander 14-point lead, lose to Lynx
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Tamika Williams outplayed her more famous
college teammate.

Williams had a career-high 22 points and added 10 rebounds
Saturday night to lead the Minnesota Lynx past Diana Taurasi and
the Phoenix Mercury, 76-68 in the first WNBA meeting of the former
Connecticut stars.

Taurasi had 13 points on 5-of-13 shooting, but the rookie hit
only one of her final eight shots and fouled out with 51.3 seconds
left.

Williams, a third-year forward, was 7-for-7 from the field and
helped the Lynx to a 29-19 edge on the boards with her fifth career
double-double.

"The most important part was we executed on offense and played
great defense," said Williams, who didn't attempt a shot longer
than four feet all night. "I think we did a good job guarding
Diana and making people take shots they're not used to taking."

Plenette Pierson had 15 points for Phoenix, which led by as much
as 14 in the first half when it shot 60.7 percent from the floor.

But Minnesota's defense clamped down in the second half, when
Phoenix went 9-for-27.

"It's only on us. The execution and the energy we brought to
the first half, we didn't quite have it in the second half,"
Taurasi said. "It's something we can fix, and I think we'll get
it."

Trailing 43-31 at halftime, the Lynx opened the second half with
a 15-2 run, taking a 46-45 lead on Williams' three-point play.

Rookie Nicole Ohlde hit three inside shots during the run and
the Mercury went cold, hitting just two of their first 10 shots.

"I was very proud of our effort in the second half," Lynx
coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "Being down by 12 at halftime,
we could have folded, but we talked about taking it one possession
at a time. I thought we executed better and made better reads. That
should give us confidence and confirm that when we do execute, how
good we can be."

Katie Smith scored 14 of her 18 points in the second half and
the Lynx hit 19 of 20 free throws in the second half. Williams, a
career 54 percent free-throw shooter, was 8-for-11 from the line.

"(Williams) has improved her free-throw shooting so much and if
other teams put her on the line, that's a dagger," Smith said.
"But the rebounding -- that's something she brings to the table
every single night."

After leaning on Williams for most of the night, the Lynx turned
to Smith to help them pull away. She scored six of Minnesota's
final eight points, including four free throws in the final minute.

"Katie Smith is a world-class player," Mercury coach Carrie
Graf said. "She showed how she uses her physicality and her body
to get calls from the referees. She's great at that."

But the key to Minnesota's victory was Williams, who entered the
game averaging 7.0 points and 7.2 assists per game.

"This is the most aggressive Tamika Williams has been so far,"
McConnell Serio said. "She was hungry tonight. She knows if she
rebounds, that will be key for us."
